This article contains proof of [[List of formulas in Riemannian geometry|formulas in Riemannian geometry]] that involve the [[Christoffel symbols]].
==Contracted Bianchi identities==
===Proof=== Start with the [[Curvature form#Bianchi identities|Bianchi identity]]<ref name="syngeandschild">{{cite book |author=Synge J.L., Schild A.|title=Tensor Calculus|year= 1949|pages=87–89-90}}</ref> :<math> R_{abmn;\ell} + R_{ab\ell m;n} + R_{abn\ell;m} = 0.</math><!-- The symbols \,\! exist to force PNG rendering; do not remove them. -->
[[Tensor contraction|Contract]] both sides of the above equation with a pair of [[metric tensor]]s: :<math> g^{bn} g^{am} (R_{abmn;\ell} + R_{ab\ell m;n} + R_{abn\ell;m}) = 0,</math>
:<math> g^{bn} (R^m {}_{bmn;\ell} - R^m {}_{bm\ell;n} + R^m {}_{bn\ell;m}) = 0,</math>
:<math> g^{bn} (R_{bn;\ell} - R_{b\ell;n} - R_b {}^m {}_{n\ell;m}) = 0,</math>
:<math> R^n {}_{n;\ell} - R^n {}_{\ell;n} - R^{nm} {}_{n\ell;m} = 0.</math> The first term on the left contracts to yield a Ricci scalar, while the third term contracts to yield a [[mixed tensor|mixed]] Ricci tensor, :<math> R_{;\ell} - R^n {}_{\ell;n} - R^m {}_{\ell;m} = 0.</math> The last two terms are the same (changing dummy index ''n'' to ''m'') and can be combined into a single term which shall be moved to the right, :<math> R_{;\ell} = 2 R^m {}_{\ell;m},</math> which is the same as :<math> 
abla_m R^m {}_\ell = {1 \over 2} 
abla_\ell R.</math> Swapping the index labels ''l'' and ''m'' yields :<math> 
abla_\ell R^\ell {}_m = {1 \over 2} 
abla_m R,</math> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; ''[[Q.E.D.]]'' &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; (''[[Riemannian geometry cheat sheet#Ricci and scalar curvatures|return to article]]'')
==The covariant divergence of the Einstein tensor vanishes==
===Proof=== The last equation in the proof above can be expressed as :<math> 
abla_\ell R^\ell {}_m - {1 \over 2} \delta^\ell {}_m 
abla_\ell R = 0</math> where δ is the [[Kronecker delta]]. Since the mixed Kronecker delta is equivalent to the mixed metric tensor, :<math> \delta^\ell {}_m = g^\ell {}_m,</math> and since the [[covariant derivative]] of the metric tensor is zero (so it can be moved in or out of the scope of any such derivative), then :<math> 
abla_\ell R^\ell {}_m - {1 \over 2} 
abla_\ell g^\ell {}_m R = 0.</math> Factor out the covariant derivative :<math> 
abla_\ell\left(R^\ell {}_m - {1 \over 2} g^\ell {}_m Right) = 0,</math> then raise the index ''m'' throughout :<math> 
abla_\ell \left(R^{\ell m} - {1 \over 2} g^{\ell m} Right) = 0.</math> The expression in parentheses is the [[Einstein tensor]], so <ref name="syngeandschild" /> :<math> 
abla_\ell G^{\ell m} = 0,</math> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;''[[Q.E.D.]]'' &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;(''[[Riemannian geometry cheat sheet#Einstein tensor|return to article]]'')
this means that the covariant divergence of the Einstein tensor vanishes.
==The Lie derivative of the metric==
===Proof=== Starting with the local [[coordinate]] formula for a covariant symmetric tensor field <math>g=g_{ab}(x^c)dx^a\otimes dx^b</math>, the [[Lie derivative]] along a [[vector field]] <math>X = X^a \partial_a</math> is :<math>  egin{align} \mathcal{L}_X g_{ab} & = X^c \partial_c g_{ab}+g_{cb}\partial_a X^c + g_{ca}\partial_b X^c \ & = X^c \partial_c g_{ab} + g_{cb} igl(\partial_a X^c\pm \Gamma^{c}_{da}X^d igr) + g_{ca} igl(\partial_b X^c \pm \Gamma^{c}_{db}X^d igr) \ & =  igl( X^c \partial_c g_{ab} - g_{cb}\Gamma^{c}_{da}X^d - g_{ca}\Gamma^{c}_{db}X^d igr)+  igl[ g_{cb} igl(\partial_a X^c + \Gamma^{c}_{da}X^d igr) + g_{ca} igl(\partial_b X^c + \Gamma^{c}_{db}X^d igr)  igr] \ & = X^c
abla_c g_{ab} + g_{cb}
abla_a X^c + g_{ca}
abla_b X^c \ & = 0 + g_{cb}
abla_a X^c + g_{ca}
abla_b X^c \ & = g_{cb}
abla_a X^c + g_{ca}
abla_b X^c \ & = 
abla_a X_b + 
abla_b X_a \end{align}</math> here, the notation <math>\partial_a =  rac{\partial}{\partial x^a}</math> means taking the [[partial derivative]] with respect to the coordinate <math> x^a</math>. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; ''[[Q.E.D.]]'' &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; (''[[Riemannian geometry cheat sheet#Ricci and scalar curvatures|return to article]]'')
